paragraph.content: Noncontrast high resolution CT of the chest performed under the following conditions:
Supine, full inspiration throughout the chest.
Supine, end expiration throughout the chest.
Prone, full inspiration from above the carina through the lung bases.
Data reconstructed as axial, sagittal, and coronal images.
Total exam Dose Length Product 569 mGy-cm.

No pulmonary consolidation or confluent pulmonary opacities. Redemonstration of mild bilateral subpleural reticulation and subpleural interstitial thickening more prominent in both lung bases which is similar to the prior examination. There is mild bilateral lower lobe bronchiectasis. Stable 5 mm subpleural right upper lobe pulmonary nodule (series 7 image 264). Stable 4 mm right lower lobe pulmonary nodule (series 7 image 256). Remonstration of a bleb or cystic structure in the right upper lobe measuring 1.7 cm. There are a few small areas of air trapping bilaterally. No pneumothorax or pleural effusion. Trachea and mainstem bronchi are patent.
Right chest stimulator device with lead extending superiorly into the neck, incompletely imaged. The visualized thyroid is unremarkable. Otherwise unremarkable.
No mediastinal or axillary lymphadenopathy. Evaluation for hilar lymphadenopathy is limited by lack of intravenous contrast.

The heart is normal in size. No pericardial effusion. Minimal coronary calcification. Mild atherosclerotic calcification of the intrathoracic aorta. Evaluation of the intrathoracic vasculature is limited without intravenous contrast.
Moderate hiatal hernia. Stomach contains ingested material. Colonic diverticulosis in the visualized portions of the colon. 1.7 cm hypodensity in the left hepatic lobe, unchanged in size.
